        PIONEERS_ALSO_CONTRIBUTE_TO_THE_ARCHIVES_EVERY_DAY                   = 7987,  -- Pioneers also contribute to the archives every day by returning from the jungle with field reports.
        IT_WOULD_NOT_DO_FOR_SOME_OF_THE                                      = 7988,  -- It would not do for some of the information contained within to be seen by common citizens. Therefore, many of those reports are relegated to the stacks for safekeeping.
        IN_SUMMATION_IT_IS_IMPOSSIBLE_TO_PROVIDE_YOU                         = 7989,  -- In summation, it is impossible to provide you with every tome from this ever-growing mass of vellum. I will need a subject via which to select a few relevant texts.
        WELL_WHAT_TOPIC_DO_YOU_SUGGEST_WE_HAVE                               = 7990,  -- Well, %, what topic do you suggest we have her look for?
        WHAT_TOPIC_SHOULD_SHE_LOOK_FOR_THE_FOUNDER                           = 7991,  -- What topic should she look for? The founder king's retinue. The founder king's battle. The founder king's death. The founder king's favorite sweets.
        D_DID_YOU_SAY_SWEETS                                                 = 7992,  -- D-did you say sweets!?
        THE_MERE_MENTION_OF_THAT_WORD_HAS_MY                                 = 7993,  -- The mere mention of that word has my tongue dancing in anticipation of the delicate waltz of saccharine flavors and--
        GULP_NO_NOW_IS_NOT_THE_TIME_FOR                                      = 7994,  -- <Gulp>... No, now is not the time for such frivolities. Let us focus on the task at hand.
        THE_FOUNDER_KING_S_RETINUE_IS_IT_WAIT                                = 7995,  -- The founder king's retinue, is it? Wait but a moment and I will return with an applicable volume.
        I_TRUST_THIS_IS_THE_SORT_OF_TOME                                     = 7996,  -- I trust this is the sort of tome for which you were searching?
        WHAT_HAVE_WE_HERE                                                    = 7997,  -- What have we here?
        THE_FOUNDER_KING_AUGUST_ADOULIN_WAS_A_CHARISMATIC                    = 7998,  -- The founder king, August Adoulin, was a charismatic personage who incited a number of valiant individuals to join his cause.
        THIS_FEAT_MIGHT_HAVE_PROVED_DIFFICULT_FOR_LESSER                     = 7999,  -- This feat might have proved difficult for lesser men, but for King August, it was child's play. His character was unimpeachable, and his gallantry nonpareil. Even those whom he defeated in combat would utter his praises before exhaling their final breath.
        EMPLOYING_THIS_UNCANNY_CHARISMA_HE_WAS_ABLE_TO                       = 8000,  -- Employing this uncanny charisma, he was able to subjugate the ferocious beasts that prowled the Adoulin Islands, unify the warlords of the various outlying islets, and establish himself as their leader.
        THESE_FORMER_WARLORDS_NUMBERED_ELEVEN_STRONG_AND_THEY                = 8001,  -- These former warlords numbered eleven strong, and they formed what would eventually be known as eleven of the Twelve Orders, excepting only the king's house.
        WITH_THE_SUPPORT_OF_HIS_ELEVEN_VASSALS_HE                            = 8002,  -- With the support of his eleven vassals, he turned his focus inward to the Ulbukan mainland and trod upon its primordial plains in hopes of taming them.
        PRESSING_EVER_FURTHER_INTO_THE_MAZE_OF_VEGETATION                    = 8003,  -- Pressing ever further into the maze of vegetation, they stumbled upon a swath of woodland now known as Yorcia Weald, wherein they encountered a tiger that loomed larger than the most expansive manse of the day and whose pelt was a radiant gold that would catch the sun's rays just right to melt the eyes of any who dared gaze upon it for more than a few moments.
        THIS_MASSIVE_BEAST_CLAIMED_TO_BE_THE_RULER                           = 8004,  -- This massive beast claimed to be the ruler of all who inhabited the jungle, and challenged the founder king with an ear-splitting roar. 'My name is Terrcualn, and you may only proceed once I lay lifeless upon the forest floor!'
        WITH_THAT_GUTTURAL_PROCLAMATION_THE_CREATURES_SURROUNDING_THE        = 8005,  -- With that guttural proclamation, the creatures surrounding the king withdrew, leaving what they assumed would be the best pickings to their pack leader.
        AS_A_REJOINDER_AUGUST_VOWED_TO_SKIN_THE                              = 8006,  -- As a rejoinder, August vowed to skin the feline alive if he laid a claw on any one of the king's followers, and the two began staring each other down in a silence that finally broke half a day hence.
        THE_BATTLE_RAGED_ON_FOR_SEVEN_SUNS_WITH                              = 8007,  -- The battle raged on for seven suns, with it ending by moonlight on the seventh night.
        NEITHER_WILDCAT_NOR_WARRIOR_COULD_DENY_THE_OTHER                     = 8008,  -- Neither wildcat nor warrior could deny the other's raw power, so they stopped the duel in favor of a long-lasting friendship.
        AS_A_SYMBOL_OF_THEIR_NEW_ALLIANCE_THE                                = 8009,  -- As a symbol of their new alliance, the tiger entrusted his son to the care of one of the king's eleven bannermen.
        THIS_IS_THE_FIRST_KNOWN_INHABITANT_WHOM_THE                          = 8010,  -- This is the first known inhabitant whom the king befriended, but it is also far from the last. August continued to push deeper into the continent's verdant abyss, where he would confront still more natives seeking to drive him from their sacred territory.
        THIS_IS_CERTAINLY_A_LOT_MORE_DESCRIPTIVE_THAN                        = 8011,  -- This is certainly a lot more descriptive than the last thing I read here.
        IT_INDULGES_IN_A_BIT_TOO_MUCH_HYPERBOLE                              = 8012,  -- It indulges in a bit too much hyperbole for my taste, but it does convey the point that their battle was hard-fought.
        EVEN_BETTER_IT_ALSO_TELLS_US_THE_ANSWER                              = 8013,  -- Even better, it also tells us the answer to Sajj'aka's question! It said the king and his feline opponent fought in Yorcia Weald, right?
        THAT_GETS_ME_TO_THINKING                                             = 8014,  -- That gets me to thinking...
        COULD_THE_GOLD_TIGER_THAT_SAVED_ME_POSSIBLY                          = 8015,  -- Could the gold tiger that saved me possibly be related to the one in this document?
        ARE_THEY_RELATED_ABSOLUTELY_SO_I_VE_HEARD                            = 8016,  -- Are they related? Absolutely. So I've heard.
        Y_YOU_ALREADY_KNEW                                                   = 8017,  -- Y-you already knew, %!?
        WHAT_HE_TOLD_YOU_HIMSELF                                             = 8018,  -- What? He told you himself?
        AH_I_GUESS_YOU_DID_SAY_SOMETHING_EARLIER                             = 8019,  -- Ah, I guess you did say something earlier about being able to communicate with him.
        HE_POSSESSES_SOME_ARCANE_POWER_BY_WHICH_HE                           = 8020,  -- He possesses some arcane power by which he can speak directly to you without having to open his mouth, right?
        THAT_DOES_SEEM_RATHER_STRANGE_BUT_I_BELIEVE                          = 8021,  -- That does seem rather strange, but I believe it since you've already shown us something similar with the leafkin matriarch. What really piques my interest, though, is how you earned his trust enough for him to tell you anything.
        THE_FOUNDER_KING_S_BATTLE_YOU_SAY_VERY                               = 8022,  -- The founder king's battle, you say? Very well, I shall march back with an appropriate document posthaste.
        OH_MY_LOOK_HERE                                                      = 8023,  -- Oh, my! %, look here!
        THE_MOST_FEARSOME_ADVERSARIES_THE_KING_AND_HIS                       = 8024,  -- The most fearsome adversaries the king and his retinue faced during the Great Expedition were the Cimmerian Adherents.
        WITH_THE_AID_OF_THE_AURELIAN_TIGER_KING                              = 8025,  -- With the aid of the aurelian tiger, King August and his forces plunged deeper and deeper into the wildlands. However, with the fall of night came heated battle with the Cimmerian Adherents--an event that was repeated seemingly ad infinitum.
        NO_MATTER_HOW_MANY_VICTORIES_THEY_EARNED_OR                          = 8026,  -- No matter how many victories they earned or how many foul creatures they dispatched, the night continued to bring with it an umbral assault. The abominations knew neither fatigue nor fear, and plagued the retinue to its breaking point.
        THE_FIENDS_REIGN_OF_TERROR_DID_NOT_STOP                              = 8027,  -- The fiends' reign of terror did not stop with the king's party, though. The creatures were said to loathe all things that drew breath or energy from the sun. They poisoned the land, blighted the trees, and massacred every animal they laid eyes upon.
        AS_THE_DAYS_PASSED_THE_KING_LEARNED_THAT                             = 8028,  -- As the days passed, the king learned that these dark minions had also beleaguered the goldpelt and his forest for countless nights.
        THIS_EPIPHANY_REDOUBLED_THEIR_DETERMINATION_NO_LONGER_WERE           = 8029,  -- This epiphany redoubled their determination. No longer were they both fighting for themselves, but for their companions as well.
        THEN_ONE_EVENFALL_A_BLOODBATH_RAINED_DOWN_UPON                       = 8030,  -- Then, one evenfall, a bloodbath rained down upon the Ulbukan jungle, tainting its lush vegetation a mournful shade of red.
        THE_EVENT_BEGAN_WITH_AN_ENEMY_AMBUSCADE_RING                         = 8031,  -- The event began with an enemy ambuscade. Ring upon ring of nocturnal horrors encircled the king and his followers. The danger became more palpable with each passing second as the shadowy grunts ilmed ever closer.
        THE_RESPLENDENT_FELINE_EXPENDED_HIS_REMAINING_STAMINA_TO             = 8032,  -- The resplendent feline expended his remaining stamina to unleash a terrifying attack that felled all the surrounding enemies. This selfless act bought the king and his companions enough time to escape, but also cost the tiger his life.
        HOW_TRAGIC_THE_TIGER_DIED_TO_PROTECT_AUGUST                          = 8033,  -- ...How tragic. The tiger died to protect August Adoulin...
        INCITED_BY_THE_DISPLAY_OF_THE_WILDCAT_S                              = 8034,  -- Incited by the display of the wildcat's bravery, his son, the king, and the monarch's eleven stalwart crusaders pressed on in the face of the nightmarish barrage.
        THE_CONFLICT_LASTED_FOR_SO_LONG_THAT_ALL                             = 8035,  -- The conflict lasted for so long that all involved lost count of the days spent cleaving chunks of flesh from their assailants. At last, however, the forces of the night were pushed back to the sorcerous ruins from which they first emerged.
        IT_WAS_THERE_THAT_THE_EXPLORERS_WERE_MET                             = 8036,  -- It was there that the explorers were met with that which controlled the entirety of the Cimmerian Adherents.
        THIS_MASTERMIND_BEHIND_THE_INVASION_OF_ULBUKA_AND                    = 8037,  -- This mastermind behind the invasion of Ulbuka and the destruction of its lands was--
        WHO_OR_WHAT_EXACTLY_REIGNED_OVER_THE_CIMMERIAN                       = 8038,  -- Who or what exactly reigned over the Cimmerian Adherents? This is getting really good.
        AW_NO_JUST_MY_LUCK_THAT_THE_MOST                                     = 8039,  -- Aw, no! Just my luck that the most important page in the entire record has been ripped out.
        BUT_WAIT_HAVEN_T_THERE_BEEN_SIGHTINGS_OF                             = 8040,  -- But wait, haven't there been sightings of beings similar to what this text calls dark minions and Cimmerian Adherents?
        IF_THAT_S_THE_CASE_THEN_WHY_ARE                                      = 8041,  -- If that's the case, then why are these creatures appearing again out of nowhere?
        THEY_SHOULD_BE_CONFINED_TO_THE_PAGES_OF                              = 8042,  -- They should be confined to the pages of history books and lines of old wives' tales, not roaming the jungle of present-day Ulbuka.
        IT_SAYS_THAT_THE_CIMMERIAN_ADHERENTS_CRAWLED_UP                      = 8043,  -- It says that the Cimmerian Adherents crawled up out of their subterranean den at the behest of some being. If only we knew its identity...
        THE_FOUNDER_KING_S_DEATH_IT_IS_THEN                                  = 8044,  -- The founder king's death it is, then. Please bear with me while I search for a script germane to it.
        I_REGRET_TO_INFORM_YOU_THAT_WHILE_SUCH                               = 8045,  -- I regret to inform you that, while such a text does exist in our records, I simply cannot find it anywhere in the closed stacks.
        WHAT_HOW_CAN_THAT_BE_IF_PEOPLE_AREN                                  = 8046,  -- What!? How can that be if people aren't able to check them out?
        WELL_ACCORDING_TO_THE_LOG_WE_GAVE_ONE                                = 8047,  -- Well, according to the log, we gave one of the ministers special permission to borrow it.
        ONE_OF_THE_MINISTERS                                                 = 8048,  -- One of the ministers?
        YES_IT_SAYS_HERE_THAT_WE_LENT_IT                                     = 8049,  -- Yes. It says here that we lent it to Melvien de Malecroix.
        MELVIEN                                                              = 8050,  -- Melvien!?
        I_AM_EXTREMELY_SORRY_FOR_BOTH_THE_INTERRUPTION                       = 8051,  -- I am extremely sorry for both the interruption and my tardiness, Andreine.
        WE_HAVE_TAKEN_MUCH_TOO_LONG_TO_RETURN                                = 8052,  -- We have taken much too long to return this tome you so kindly lent us from the closed stacks.
        WHY_LADY_ARCIELA_WITH_IN_TOW                                         = 8053,  -- Why, Lady Arciela...with % in tow.
        I_DID_NOT_EXPECT_TO_SEE_YOU_TWO                                      = 8054,  -- I did not expect to see you two here. What, may I ask, is it that you have come to research?
        OH_PERHAPS_WE_SHOULD_CONTINUE_THIS_DISCUSSION_AFTER                  = 8055,  -- Oh, perhaps we should continue this discussion after I finish what I came here to do.
        YOU_SEE_LORD_DE_MALECROIX_S_BUTLER_INFORMED                          = 8056,  -- You see, Lord de Malecroix's butler informed me that a rather peculiar tome emblazoned with the Celennia Library's seal had been lying on his desk for an extended period of time.
        HOWEVER_THE_MINISTER_HIMSELF_IS_INDISPOSED_AT_THE                    = 8057,  -- However, the minister himself is...indisposed at the moment.
        AS_LUCK_WOULD_HAVE_IT_I_HAD_BUSINESS                                 = 8058,  -- As luck would have it, I had business to conduct in the vicinity, so I am here in his stead.
        THANK_YOU_SO_MUCH_FOR_YOUR_DILIGENCE_ESTIENNEUX                      = 8059,  -- Thank you so much for your diligence, Estienneux, and I am sorry you had to...
        AHHH_THIS_IS_IT_ARCIELA_THIS_IS_THE                                  = 8060,  -- Ahhh, this is it! Arciela, %, this is the book I was talking about!
        IT_IS_THE_ONLY_ONE_IN_OUR_ARCHIVES                                   = 8061,  -- It is the only one in our archives that deals with the death of the founder king.
        I_GOT_THE_IMPRESSION_THAT_LORD_DE_MALECROIX                          = 8062,  -- I got the impression that Lord de Malecroix was particularly concerned with the contents of that text. I would often see his nose buried within its pages. I surmise that was the reason it had yet to be returned.
        WELL_IF_HE_WAS_SO_ENTHRALLED_WITH_IT                                 = 8063,  -- Well, if he was so enthralled with it that he could hardly put it down...
        LET_S_NOT_WASTE_ANY_TIME_SKIP_PAST                                   = 8064,  -- Let's not waste any time, %! Skip past the table of contents and on to the real text!
        NOT_A_SOUL_BORE_WITNESS_TO_THE_KING                                  = 8065,  -- ...Not a soul bore witness to the king's demise.
        THE_KING_AND_HIS_FOLLOWERS_STEPPED_INTO_THOSE                        = 8066,  -- The king and his followers stepped into those mysterious ruins, wherein the "Serpentine Labyrinth"--dubbed such due to the fact it contained as many branching passageways as leaves in the jungle--sprawled before them.
        THE_SERPENTINE_LABYRINTH_DOES_THAT_SOUND_LIKE_ANYTHING               = 8067,  -- The Serpentine Labyrinth? Does that sound like anything you've heard of before, %?
        HAVE_YOU_HEARD_OF_IT_BEFORE_IT_SOUNDS                                = 8068,  -- Have you heard of it before? It sounds like Ra'Kaznar. Not in the least.
        IS_THAT_THE_ANCIENT_STRUCTURE_EMBEDDED_WITHIN_THE                    = 8069,  -- Is that the ancient structure embedded within the crags of Kamihr Drifts?
        NOW_THAT_YOU_MENTION_IT_I_DO_RECALL                                  = 8070,  -- Now that you mention it, I do recall a story from my youth about a certain old building buried deep underground...
        RA_KAZNAR_AND_THIS_SERPENTINE_LABYRINTH_COULD_VERY                   = 8071,  -- Ra'Kaznar and this Serpentine Labyrinth could very well be one and the same.
        I_SEE_I_GUESS_THE_TEXT_IS_PRETTY                                     = 8072,  -- I see. I guess the text is pretty vague.
        UGH_IF_ONLY_I_COULD_FULLY_REMEMBER_I                                 = 8073,  -- Ugh, if only I could fully remember. I swear I was told a story about some old building buried deep beneath the earth when I was a kid, but I can't recall any of the details.
        I_ALWAYS_ASSUMED_SUCH_TALES_WERE_ONLY_TOLD                           = 8074,  -- I always assumed such tales were only told to scare children or stimulate their imaginations, but maybe there is some truth to this one after all.
        EITHER_WAY_LET_S_CONTINUE_READING_BEFORE_WE                          = 8075,  -- Either way, let's continue reading before we jump to any conclusions.
        THE_HORDES_OF_UNCANNY_TERRORS_THAT_CRAWLED_ABOVEGROUND               = 8076,  -- The hordes of uncanny terrors that crawled aboveground to corrupt the land all did so from that very labyrinth.
        BY_THIS_TIME_THE_KING_S_RANKS_HAD                                    = 8077,  -- By this time, the king's ranks had been thinned by the droves of aberrations that had already fallen to the heroes' blades. However, that did not the least to shorten his strides into this den of iniquity.
        EACH_FOOTFALL_THEY_TOOK_RESOUNDED_WITH_A_BOOMING                     = 8078,  -- Each footfall they took resounded with a booming determination to prevent this caliginous menace from ever resurfacing.
        AND_YET_WITH_THE_EXCEPTION_OF_ONE_SUBORDINATE                        = 8079,  -- And yet, with the exception of one subordinate, the steps of every person who made the descent with King August were silenced within that abyssal mausoleum.
        THE_LONE_PERSON_TO_SURVIVE_WAS_MORIMAR_THE                           = 8080,  -- The lone person to survive was Morimar, the king's general and tamer of beasts. He emerged from the chaos with the golden tiger's next of kin, and no one else.
        WITH_THE_FOUNDER_KING_NOWHERE_TO_BE_SEEN                             = 8081,  -- With the founder king nowhere to be seen and most of Morimar's account lost to the slow tick of time, all we can do is conjecture about the king's fate.
        THAT_CONJECTURE_SADLY_CAN_ONLY_BE_BASED_UPON                         = 8082,  -- That conjecture, sadly, can only be based upon the few curt words his general spoke of the terrible incident.
        FROM_THEM_WE_CAN_CONCLUDE_THAT_KING_AUGUST                           = 8083,  -- From them, we can conclude that King August expended his life inside the bowels of the Serpentine Labyrinth, clashing with--
        FOR_THE_GODDESS_S_SAKE_THE_REST_OF                                   = 8084,  -- For the Goddess's sake, the rest of this tome is completely illegible!
        THE_BATTLE_WAS_A_SPECTACLE_OF_ATROCIOUS_BEAUTY                       = 8085,  -- The battle was a spectacle of atrocious beauty, with hacked limbs and ruptured veins decorating each and every winding corridor of the subterranean maze.
        EXPLORER_AFTER_EXPLORER_IN_THE_KING_S_RETINUE                        = 8086,  -- Explorer after explorer in the king's retinue was struck down, but not before they could drag regiments of oppressors to the grave with them.
        KING_AUGUST_USED_HIMSELF_AS_A_SHIELD_TO                              = 8087,  -- King August used himself as a shield to allow Morimar time with which to return soilside. With little to no room for error and even less for respite, the monarch's chances of climbing back up from those treacherous depths were lamentably slim.
        MORIMAR_HURRIED_BACK_TO_CASTLE_ADOULIN_THE_KING                      = 8088,  -- Morimar hurried back to Castle Adoulin, the king's cherished blade swinging from his side and a message from the sovereign on his lips: 'No more shall we colonize the hinterland.' With that, he passed the sword on to the callow prince and princess and promptly departed.
        ORTHARSYNE                                                           = 8089,  -- Ortharsyne...
        HIS_ORDERS_FULFILLED_MORIMAR_VANISHED_FROM_SIGHT_NEVER               = 8090,  -- His orders fulfilled, Morimar vanished from sight, never to be seen again.
        EVEN_AFTER_HIS_DISAPPEARANCE_TALES_OF_HIS_AND                        = 8091,  -- Even after his disappearance, tales of his and his feline companion's efforts to preserve the forest waft above the heads of citizens throughout Adoulin's bifurcated districts to this day.
        SO_KING_AUGUST_NEVER_DID_MAKE_IT_BACK                                = 8092,  -- So...King August never did make it back aboveground...
        THEN_HIS_GRAVE_IN_RALA_WATERWAYS_IS_NOTHING                          = 8093,  -- Then his grave in Rala Waterways is nothing but a memorial.
        HAVE_ANYTHING_TO_SAY_HIS_GRAVE_IN_THE                                = 8094,  -- Have anything to say? His grave in the waterways? Just a memorial?
        THERE_S_A_SEPULCHER_THAT_WAS_ERECTED_IN                              = 8095,  -- There's a sepulcher that was erected in the Rala Waterways for the founder king.
        I_ALWAYS_ASSUMED_THAT_HIS_BODY_WAS_ENTOMBED                          = 8096,  -- I always assumed that his body was entombed there, but that doesn't seem to be the case...
        THAT_IS_THE_FIRST_I_HAVE_HEARD_OF                                    = 8097,  -- That is the first I have heard of this as well.
        PERHAPS_CHANCELLOR_YGNAS_COULD_PROVIDE_SOME_INSIGHT_INTO             = 8098,  -- Perhaps Chancellor Ygnas could provide some insight into this quandary?
        MAYBE                                                                = 8099,  -- Maybe...
        ALTHOUGH_I_SUPPOSE_YOUR_FATHER_ALSO_DISAPPEARED_UNDER                = 8100,  -- Although I suppose your father also disappeared under peculiar circumstances. He may not have told Ygnas anything.
        OH_HOW_THOUGHTLESS_OF_ME_I_SHOULD_NOT                                = 8101,  -- ...Oh, how thoughtless of me. I should not have touched upon such an obviously sensitive issue.
        ASK_ABOUT_HER_FATHER_S_DISAPPEARANCE_OF_COURSE                       = 8102,  -- Ask about her father's disappearance? Of course...since he brought it up! No, it would be boorish of me.
        HAVE_YOU_ACUEXES_LIVING_IN_YOUR_EARS_DID                             = 8103,  -- Have you acuexes living in your ears!? Did you not just hear that it is a delicate subject for the princess!?
        I_CARE_NOT_WHETHER_YOU_ARE_A_VENERATED                               = 8104,  -- I care not whether you are a venerated pioneer, there are some topics you simply do not broach...no matter your station.
        IT_S_ALRIGHT_I_DON_T_MIND                                            = 8105,  -- It's alright. I...don't mind.
        IT_NEVER_OCCURRED_TO_ME_THAT_BUILDING_A                              = 8106,  -- It never occurred to me that building a grave beneath the city amongst a series of canals was odd, but thinking it over...
        WHY_NOT_ERECT_A_MONUMENT_IN_ONE_OF                                   = 8107,  -- Why not erect a monument in one of the plazas where everyone can see it?
        ANYWAY_WE_VE_DONE_OUR_JOB_RESEARCHING                                = 8108,  -- Anyway, we've done our job researching.
        THE_CIMMERIAN_ADHERENTS_THE_SERPENTINE_LABYRINTH_THE_TRUTH           = 8109,  -- The Cimmerian Adherents, the Serpentine Labyrinth, the truth about the founder king's grave...
        I_FEEL_LIKE_I_HAVE_MORE_QUESTIONS_NOW                                = 8110,  -- I feel like I have more questions now than when we first came in, but this should be more than enough to appease that surly serpent.
        LET_S_MAKE_OUR_WAY_BACK_TO_MOUNT                                     = 8111,  -- Let's make our way back to Mount Kamihr and find out once and for all what's ravaging the jungle!
        OH_HELLO_I_VE_BEEN_SEARCHING_AND_SEARCHING                           = 8112,  -- Oh, hello, %! I've been searching and searching, but haven't yet come up with anything of interest.
        HOW_ABOUT_YOU                                                        = 8113,  -- How about you?
        WHAT_WILL_YOU_DO_SHOW_HER_A_SCALE                                    = 8114,  -- What will you do? Show her a scale. Ask about the Serpentine Labyrinth. Cheer Arciela on.
        YOU_SAY_THIS_IS_ONE_OF_HIS_SCALES                                    = 8115,  -- You say this is one of his scales? I thought it would be more...physical in form. Or does it look like this because it was sealed away for so long?
        ITS_LIGHT_IS_SO_COMFORTINGLY_WARM_YET_THE                            = 8116,  -- Its light is so comfortingly warm, yet the scale itself is so frail... Perhaps there are more left to be found.
        I_VE_TAKEN_A_GOOD_LOOK_AT_THE                                        = 8117,  -- I've taken a good look at the documents here in the closed stacks, and we were right in thinking that the Serpentine Labyrinth and Ra'Kaznar are the same place.
